reviewText:
Home is an excellent documentary which aims to familiarize us with our planet while reminding us of our place and responsibilities vis--vis our environment.
The amount of effort and research put into this project is evident and as a result the documentary helps transport the viewer to different locations allowing one to lay eyes on natural wonders and disasters alike. Glenn Close does an amazing job narrating in a way that brings to mind the Lords of the Rings, while the photography is simply breathtaking!
In short, Home is a must-see documentary, strongly recommended to those people that do care about the legacy they leave behind for the generations to come. 5 Stars

One may not agree with the theory of evolution, but that should not be the reason for not watching/buying this DVD.  This film is about man's greed and the results.  We must become stewards of our planet or face the fact that our children or grandchildren may likely suffer unthinkable changes to our (American)wealthy way of life.  This film shows what has already happened in my lifetime of 60 years, and has certainly awakened my family to our responsibility to care for our home.  The photography is absolutely exquisite, the music haunting, and the narrative poetic.

This documentary will move you and scare you.  The visuals rival that of "Planet Earth" released a few years ago.  The colors are simply stunning.  The truth told in this film is mind boggling.  For those that still don't believe - watch the movie.  If after that point you can still sit there and say we have NO impact on our home, then - there is nothing that can be done for your ignorance.

Get the movie.  It will be money well spent!

The beginning of the theatrical trailer immediately tells you this is a production based on evolution.  "Life, a miracle that began around 4 billion years ago" is how this production starts.  No thank you.  The filming may be breath taking but it is not worth the scripting.  Planet Earth is better quality and they do a wonderful job at keeping to the facts, not fiction.

This is a magnificent production. I'm now watching it on the National Geographic channel and had to check to see if a DVD was available. No commercials to interrupt the thread!

The photography is stunning, the music enjoyably fitting and the narrator's voice smooth and clear. The story is informative, sad and scary.

Yes, this production conveys the message that the current economic model of consumption is not conducive to long-term survival (in the manner to which we have become accustomed) where a secure supply of uncontaminated food/water and adequate shelter/clothing are a given.

Sometimes "a picture is worth a thousand words".

This is a great documentary film! The images and shots were movingly stunning, the colors were amazingly rich and fluid.
THe narrative highlighted the problems that we've created with literature-worthy eloquence and with objectivity whilst not forgetting humanity's needs. The mostadmirable part of it was that while it instills a sense of pain and regret for the environment, it focuses on what we still have and what we can still save. But behind every good narrative, there is a good soundtrack and the one for this documentary lives up to its narrative, with music from all corners of the globe, each fitting into its place and each a place where it fits.

One extremely noteworthy aspect of narrative,picture and soundtrack mixing well is that the soundtrack doesn't drown out the narrative, as some documentaries are won't to do. Also, the documentary allows for moments of wordless eloquence to captivate the viewer in sound and image - yet without dragging it to being "verbose".

all in all, the five stars awarded are truly deserved.
one for picture, one for mastery of language in narration, one for soundtrack, one for humanity the last one, for message and overall delivery.

This movie is very sweet, and I really like the concept. The script is smart and hands out wisdom and humor in judicious doses. The characters are sympathetic, and some of the messages are relevant to real-life global issues, both in history and in present day. The first time we watched this, we weren't sure about some of the music, but upon a second viewing, we grew fonder of the soundtrack. The reason I'm giving this four stars rather than five is that there is some language and some violence that is unnecessary. I don't think it's inappropriate, exactly, but I think the movie would be much improved if the words/actions were eliminated. The sentiments of anger and frustration could easily be conveyed in a different, perhaps more effective, manner. Our kids (7, 5, and 2) all liked this movie, but I would have felt more comfortable showing it to my younger two if there were less vitriol and pushing/shoving. Check out the book that this movie is based on: The True Meaning of Smekday, if you're interested in the origins of this story.

I am almost 30 and I love this movie. It's a heartfelt story about an alien arriving on Earth with it's species. All humans have been put into a relocation center - that the aliens think is "better" and "nice" because it's filled with games and candy. One little girl accidentally was left in the city, and becomes a traveling companion for the alien. He made a mistake and is trying to run away, and she is trying to find her mom with her faithful cat named Pig. It's hilarious and cute. I haven't laughed this hard in a kids movie - for kid humor - in years. Despite my normal dislike of pop music, I love the soundtrack. It's very fitting.

Potential Cons
I am not a parents, but I do teach English as a Second Language, so I feel it should be noted that the alien speaks very poor English. He mixes up words since it is his Second Language and he messes up words. For example, he calls exiting a cupboard into the main room going "into the out." He drops prepositions and articles sometimes as well. He constantly messes up "my mom." While this adds to the cuteness and the humor, if you have a toddler learning to speak, it might be confusing. I'm not sure, as I said, I have no children. Personally, I now tell my kitties that they need to go "into the out now" when I want them to go on the balcony. : )

..humans stand to lose in the next extinction event that we are concerned.  We shouldn't be.  That event is on its way like it or not. There have been several eradications of life on this planet, and whether we finish sawing the limb we are sitting on and suffocate, dehydrate or starve, or an asteroid splashes into Kansas and eliminates us and everything else in a flash, our end will come.  We somehow think we are special, but really our lives are no more valuable to this planet than the dinosaurs or the passenger pigeons.  To paraphrase Darwin, the ultimate fate of all species is extinction.  We will be no different, and truthfully, the Earth will be better off without us.  No species has done the damage here we have.  We should be ashamed, but we seem to be proud of it, and we have all been told what happens to the proud.  My only real fear is that we are able to leave Earth before we are eliminated, and spread the virus of our kind to other worlds only to rape those as well.

Filled with fear mongering. Before you buy into the scare tactics of this movie, enter into Google the exact opposite of this movie's supposed "facts," to see what thousands of other scientists think about these issues. Alarmists would have you think nearly all men of reason believe in MANMADE warming (not the sun, etc)...that such things as cow farts and SUVs destroy the planet, without telling you how much $$$ is being made having "useful idiots" convinced. What they don't tell you should scare you. The individuals and groups running away with the $$$ should scare you. Poor little children think polar bears are in great danger. Google that one, for starters. Students who buy into the lies think that just because some information comes from NASA, it must be true, forgetting how politicized all bureaucracies are. Think about it:  has there ever in the history of the world, been so much money gathered on one place (D.C.)? Money to be spread around. Money to be stolen. In the shadows, they're laughing all the way to the bank, while these types of documentaries are churned out so no one is "the wiser."

The 1 star is the fact that the earth has not been around more than 6 thousand years, the lies are never ending, and some of it is true but you have to have an open mind and common sense, and free will. The breathtaking beauty, awesomeness and amazing footage and photography is 100 stars. I like Glenn Close but don't agree with all the lies, deceit, lies and deceit, and lies in this documentary. Everyone has free will to decide and believe, and there is tons of information to be learned. I suggest "Beginnings" and the many documentaries available on Amazon Prime are astonishing, where truth is actually proven. Brought here by the cult fanaticism behind this movie, I was disappointed by frenetic animation, clumsy scene direction, and poorly chosen voice casts and acting (IE Rhianna). Time does not flow cohesively throughout the story and main conflicts and antagonists are rushed or not prefaced. The movie plays out as one big montage, with superfluous use of establishing shots and impractical character actions. Animation errors are abundant in this film; with disappearing background objects, clipping issues, and miscellaneous masses and physics applied to characters and objects. Don't expect anything interesting in terms of scifi -- this is built very much like a children'ts book, and I lost interest when the "tuned up super car" was powered by slushies, bubbles, and ticker tape.

The saving grace to this film was Parsons' casting as "Oh". His talents shine through and give substance to an otherwise dry, bland, and flakey cast of characters. Parson's effectively communicates the character he plays, which leaves a stark contrast with Rhianna as Tip. For a movie supposedly promoting cultural diversity, little of ethnicity is discussed or implied -- save for the big name celebrities they tacked onto the film. Oftentimes Tip's voice acting underwhelming and did not sync up to her lips or actions, further there is little in the way to empathize her character or establish backstory.

Overall this is a movie suited for audiences under 5 years, I would not recommend this to adults or older children as it has a tendency to speak down to its audience.

I love this movie for so many reasons! Touches on so many topics/lessons for kids and is adorable as well! Initially I thought it might be annoying or for really young kids based on the cover picture, but this isn't the case at all!

Love the lessons on diversity, accepting other cultures vs believing you are superior/smarter, etc, understanding emotions, consequences of mistreating others & being reckless, appreciation of art, power of music and dancing, being unique & different, taking perspective of others, friendship & family, loyalty & sacrifice vs selfishness, bravery, and more.

I also love that the main character is a beautiful black girl with curly hair and possibly hispanic mother? instead of white like so many movies are. I like that media is finally (though slowly) catching up to real culture. This is especially great for the girls I nanny for, who are half white/black and asked why so many Disney movies have girls with light skin and straight/wavy hair instead of darker skin and curly hair like theirs. They already talk about wanting straight hair and how their dolls with lighter skin are prettier, which is heartbreaking. The girl is also in 7th grade, and movie appeals to both younger and older kids, while also being entertaining for adults! :)

Contrived, boring and unoriginal, this was a chore of bland CG and sappy, predictable writing. Basically a reboot of 'Lilo and Stitch' with a tired plot about a girl befriending an alien to find her lost mom (and why is it that we can buy into a story about aliens driving flying cars utilizing slushee parts, yet its completely impossible to find a decent, loving DAD in Hollywood stories anymore?) The "humor" is dry and tedious (and it seemed like the leader of these aliens is little more than a rip-off of King Julien from Madagascar, particularly the accent.) The symbolism seems like something out of a bad film interpretation class: aliens who flee in soft bubble spaceship and an evil alien in a massive, pointy sharp triangular ship.... give me a break. What a predictable bore.

Theres an alien race of Boogs.  Theyre fearful little octopuses, and are careful with emotions.  But they're peaceful enough, and they are looking for a new world where them might be safe from angry planet destroying pyramids.  Soearth, right?  Yeah, they come to earth and one of their outcast members, Oh (voiced by The Big Bang Theorys Jim Parsons), meets the orphaned Tip (voiced by Rihanna, who doesnt sound anything like a little girl) and together they strike up an unlikely friendship.  Youd think an alien with superior technology could teach an earth kid a thing or two but, nope!  Our kids are so dumb they cant even learn from superior beings!  Tip, actually, is both sad and precocious; shes sadocious.  She lost her mom but knows how to scrape by and singyou know, because shes voiced by Rihanna.  Well, she teaches Oh a thing or two about living life without fear, about emotional intelligence, and together they find her mom and save the earth and save the Boogs.  The end.

The movies bright, has a thumpin soundtrack, and is touchy-feely sentimental.  It also tries too hard.  Kids should like it.  Not so much here thrown in special for the adults but there's a lot of (pretty average) musically themed special features.  You know, to add life to the party.

I've been watching Pixar movies since Pixar was a small open source company recently purchased by Steven Jobs for a couple of million dollars and long before they had any affiliation with Disney.  In terms of plot, execution, and creativity, this movie stands up to any of the Disney Pixar films.  Beyond this, it's funny, perfectly delightful, contains important lessons on cultural hegemony, and includes a thought provoking and completely surprising twist ending.  So I as quite shocked when I came to purchase it Amazon (I've watched it on Netflix streaming half a dozen times with my kids) and noticed the large number of 1-star reviews.  WTF?  Then it hit me: the main characters are a teenage black girl from Barbados (voiced by Rihanna, also from Barbados) and an alien voiced by an openly gay actor who plays a physicist on a popular TV show.  This is likely quite upsetting to racists and Christian superstitionists offended by the idea of smart black girls and alien life forms that view humans as an inferior species.  So, if you are a racist offended by the idea of teenage black female lead character or a superstitious human exceptionalist, you probably should avoid this film.  Otherwise, I absolutely love this movie and don't mind watching it over and over again with my kids (ages 4.5 and 6.5) who love it just as much as I do.

They don't hurt the humans but rather move them all to one spot on earth. Eventually the reason the aliens are on the planets is solved and you have a happy ending. It seems to have a lesson of acceptance by the aliens finding out their enemy isn't actually an enemy but a misunderstanding. A human kid ends up becoming friends with an alien which is when the alien helps her find her mother - accepting each other and working to accomplish the goal.

I sort of fell in love with this movie without expecting to.  It was kind of ridiculous I wound up watching the rental so many times to the point that I just bought it when I saw it at the store lol.. I think it's difficult when you only review things you love (or super dislike) - I should probably review more but when you see others making similar comments for or against something it's easy to just let them say it.

 For me the movie had so many elements and layers that you don't often find in animated films. The writing was great, I find myself quoting Boov from time to time now. The Boov (purple creature on the cover) had control of everything in the galaxy for the most part and thought that they were right about everything but it took a series of events to help them begin to understand that other beings have feelings and a right to live a good life of their own making as well.  Once that became more clear suddenly the truth of the various infringements on the rights of others became more obvious and there was a new willingness to  reach out and be vulnerable and correct those wrongs.  It was also a feel-good story on ways that  when people's lives get turned upside down, they can still find ways to get back to the people/things they care about and make things right.  Kids and parents who have been through a lot or who would like to understand others who have, would probably really appreciate it.

Story was ok, characters were interesting to see play out, it wasn't a polished finished product and the voice of the purple guy grated on my nerves pretty heavily (he's supposed to be unloved so I guess it was in character, but it made me want to hit mute or turn it off multiple times... congratulations to the voice actor for being genuinely annoying I guess?)

It's a bit stretched long and the transition between scenes and plot elements is sometimes pretty forced and awkward - it could have benefitted from a bit of quality editing and a writer who could do character interaction and plot development at the same time instead of having one or the other - or usually one, and then the other tacked on or crowbarred into a scene.

And kids won't care but all of the plot devices / macguffins / etc are just so forced in this thing... nothing makes any damn sense.

All that said? Kids enjoyed it, good ending (when it finally came) and some fun ideas (slushie powered car, learning to see that things aren't what they say they are / what they seem) and the kids voice actor wasn't bad.

This is a beautiful movie about friendly aliens named the Boov invading Earth. Boov are a race who praise running away from danger and not taking chances and frown on uniqueness, friendship, parties, and especially making too many mistakes. But among the Boov is a strange, humorous fella named Oh, who loves making friends and hosting parties, is very unique, and makes many, hilarious accidental mistakes. It isn't until he runs into a spunky human girl named Tip that he realizes that mistakes are part of life, and that uniqueness is something to be celebrated, and even when things seem darkest, the power of Hope and love can do amazing things, and that he can find home and friendship in unlikely places. This hilarious movie features Jim Parsons (Sheldon from the Big Bang Theory) as Oh, Rhianna as Gratuity "Tip" Tucchi, Steve Martin (Orin Scrivello D.D.S. from Little Shop of Horrors, among other things) As the hilarious leader of the Boov: Captain Smeck, and Jennifer Lopez as Lucy Tucchi, Tip's "Mimom".

This Blu-ray edition has the movie in beautiful high definition, which is a visual feast with all the detail and the bubbles and the gravity balls flying around. Then there are the special features, which this Blu-Ray has ALOT. It has a dance video called "Oh's" Shake your Boov thing" " Two versions of The Feel the Light music video, Oh's Boovy Juke Box featuring music and scenes from the film (This can be long), two hilarious little features, one mentioning all the bonus features on the disc and another being Tips from Oh about how to throw parties, a costume game, 3 brilliant short films ("This is Being Boov" giving you more info about the Boov, "Almost Home" which is a prequel to Home used as a trailer in theaters showing how the Boov found Earth, and the "Boov Testing Lab", showing how the Boov found out about Earth things. It has deleted scenes, how to draw featurettes, a meet the cast video, a trailer, a look into the world of dream works animation (mostly music videos and trailers for other movies) and a gallery of image stills from the Home Movie. If you're a DreamWorks fan, an animation fan, or just love movies, this is a good one for you.

It also had some great humorous moments for the adults, too. I really like Jim Parsons as the alien, Oh. He is very funny with his alien views of our ordinary world. Its a fun, entertaining adventure to just sit back and enjoy without over thinking it. It also has nice take-a-way messages about courage, family and friendship.

A very cute movie about what happens when two worlds collide!  Tip (Gratuity) Tucci (played by Rhianna), is a fierce, passionate young girl who finds herself alone on an alien-overrun Earth.  After narrowly escaping capture from the Boov invasion, she and her fat cat (Pig), come into contact with "O," the outcast Boov (played by Jim Parsons).  Very funny adventures as both Tip and O journey through the world to find Tip's missing Mother (Jennifer Lopez).  A story about friendship, loyalty, the importance of family, and finding yourself and strengths under sometimes radical conditions.  My girls love this movie, and it has a great soundtrack!

I really like this movie.  It's got a really great premise for a few themes in the movie.  The fact that the "Boov" believe they are so superior to humans, but "Oh" discovers that just because you think you might be better than someone or something else, doesn't mean it's true.  TIp also makes a journey of her own to understand that "Oh" and the "Boov" can change.  It's a movie that shows the value of getting to understand a culture that you might not be familiar with before you judge the way someone from that culture does something.  It's got a lot of cute insider jokes in it that will appeal to adults (at the end in the party one of the Boov has a "screw drive" drink that latterly includes a Screw driver in it) and a lot of up front kid geared jokes that the kids will love (eating the blue deodorizer in the urinal...what kid hasn't thought about trying a little bite of that...come on...admit it...everyone has wondered about those blue tabs!).  The party addition isn't that all that special.  There are a few added features, but mostly I got it for the movie.  The disks were packaged well and arrived on time.

This is definitely one for the kiddies! The jokes are pretty weak at that Oh character becomes pretty annoying after a while. Its about an alien race, the Boov's, who take over earth so they can escape the evil Gorg. The Boov's spend time reorganising earth by getting rid of things that they find useless, whilst Oh is struggling to find friends and is unable to fit in with his fellow Boov's. Tip, voiced by Rihanna, manages to escape from the Boov's with her cat and she is finding it hard to cope with the fact that they had taken her mum. She then bumps into Oh, who is on the run because he sent out an invitation for his party, to the whole of the Boov colony which will blow there cover and eventually reach Gorg. Oh and Tip then end up on a mission to find Tips mum and save Oh's planet. I did find the jokes more silly than funny and it was extremely corny in parts. There's not that much material for adults and it amazed me how intelligent Oh turned out to be towards the end. On the plus side, the animation does look great and the attention to detail is impressive but I found myself cringing through most of the film. Don't get me wrong, it's the perfect movie for keeping the kids quiet because they will definitely love it but from an adults point of view, it just didn't work for me. Average!

Round-Up: I've always found Jim Parsons voice pretty annoying, after watching a few episodes of the Big Bang Theory and you really can tell that they modeled the Oh character around his mannerisms and weird one liners. He was a good choice to play Oh but it just became a bit too much after a while. There wasn't that much to Rihanna's character (Tip) but I did giggle when Captain Smek (Steve Martin) was using earth things, like a hoover and a hair dryer, in the completely wrong way. Anyway, the movie was directed by Tim Johnson who also made Antz, Over The Hedge, Sinbad: Legend of the Seas and Kung Fu Panda Holiday. Because of the time that it takes to makes these animation movies, I'm not surprised that he hasn't made that many but he has made enough profit from this film and Antz, to bank roll other projects in the future. Although this movie wasn't for me, it's great for a family day out and it's harmless fun for all ages.

Sometimes, when you watch an animated movie because one of the characters is voiced by someone you like to watch on tv, you get a gem - for me, this was the case with Pixar's Inside Out, which I found out only through an interview with Lewis Black and which greatly exceeded my expectations.

Not so with this poorly executed animation, which I admittedly watched only because I love Jim Parsons as Dr. Sheldon Cooper in The Big Bang Theory. But his acting skills - so obviously front-and-center in TBBT - couldn't hope to save this god-awful, boring and not even moderately entertaining fiasco. I'm not a fan of dumbed-down language to begin with, so the fact that the BOOV (which would've more aptly been named BOO) are apparently speaking in some gibberish that is part texting language, part Yoda speak, was already irritating from the get go. But then the movie progressed and JUST. KEPT. GETTING. WORSE.

I don't know what's more ridiculous - the lacking dialogue, the Boov enemy called Gorg (I guess Star Trek has a monopoly on Borg so changing just one letter was appropriate - groan!), the female character incongruously named Gratuity ("my friends call me Tip"), the constant streaming of presumably peppy, teeny bopper pop music...It's absolutely barf-tastic.

Not all adults enjoy animated movies, but I'm one of those who do when they're well made. This, sadly, is NOT well-made and clearly seems designed to capitalize on the rising star of Jim Parsons by giving him a lead (voice) role.

Personally, I think the making of animated movies should be left to the people who actually know what they're doing: PIXAR. Everyone else seems to be inept at combining cartoon-style movies with any sort of substantial dialogue and/or story line. I don't know how anyone could actually enjoy watching this and I found that the lacking content completely failed to successfully bring across any "hidden meaning" that would've given this overly silly movie some depth.

3.5 stars. It's no Toy Story, but it's sweet, touching and charming. Parson's voice is an acquired taste, but Rihanna does a wonderful job voicing the girl. It could have used a bit more story, but then again the last few scenes had everyone in this household smiling while sniffling back tears. It does
sometimes feel like you're watching an extended Rihanna-and-J-Lo music video. Then again, their songs, and the whole soundtrack, are excellent, and you're pretty much guaranteed to have them circling around in your head for the next several days. Not the best animated feature ever made, but pretty darn good and much better than the critics led us to believe.
